KDPI and EPTS

1. KDRI and KDPI

1.1 Introduction

In the field of kidney transplantation, evaluating the quality of donor kidneys is crucial due to the persistent shortage of available organs. Two important indices have been developed to assess donor quality: the Kidney Donor Risk Index (KDRI) and the Kidney Donor Profile Index (KDPI).

1.2 The Kidney Donor Risk Index (KDRI)

1.2.1 Definition and Purpose

The KDRI is a continuous metric that quantifies the relative risk of graft failure, which was defined as return to dialysis, reâ€‘transplant, or death, after kidney transplantation from a deceased donor. It provides a way to compare donor kidneys based on clinical and demographic factors.

1.2.2 Origin and Reference

The KDRI model was first proposed by Rao etÂ al.Â (2009) in the journal Transplantation\(^{1}\). It is based on a multivariable Cox proportional hazards model that estimated the hazard of graft loss or death after transplantation. Global model fit was calculated using discrimination (concordance = 0.6, also known as the C-statistic) and calibration (Integrated Brier score = 0.13).

1.2.3 Model Formula

The stratified Cox model underlying the KDRI is

\[ h(t \mid \mathbf Z, s) \,=\, h_{0,s}(t)\, \exp(\boldsymbol\beta^{\!\top}\mathbf Z), \]

where

  • \(\mathbf Z = (Z_1,\ldots,Z_p)\) is the covariate vector for the \(p=8\) donor factors listed in SectionÂ 1.2.4;
  • \(s\) indexes the stratum determined by transplant centre, singleâ€‘year recipient age, and recipient diabetes status. (not straified by OPO)
  • \(h_{0,s}(t)\) is the baseline hazard in stratumÂ \(s\).

Hence, the Kidney Donor Risk Index for donorÂ \(i\) is

\[ \text{KDRI}_i\;=\;\frac{h(t\mid \mathbf Z_i)}{h(t\mid \mathbf Z_{\text{ref}})} \,=\, \exp\!\Bigl\{\boldsymbol\beta^{\!\top}(\mathbf Z_i-\mathbf Z_{\text{ref}})\Bigr\} \,=\,\prod_{j=1}^{p} \mathrm{HR}_j^{\,Z_{ij}-Z_{\text{ref},j}},\qquad \mathrm{HR}_j \equiv e^{\beta_j}. \]

1.2.4 Model Variables

RaoÂ etÂ al. initially included 10 donor factors. In the current OPTN operational model (approved OctoberÂ 2024) this has been streamlined to 8 donor factors:

  1. Donor ageÂ (yrs)
  2. Donor heightÂ (cm)
  3. Donor weightÂ (kg)
  4. History of hypertensionÂ (yes/no)
  5. History of diabetesÂ (yes/no)
  6. Cause of deathÂ (cerebrovascular accidentÂ vsÂ other)
  7. Serum creatinineÂ (mg/dL)
  8. Donation after cardiac death (DCD, yes/no)

Black race and hepatitisÂ C virus (HCV) seropositivity were removed during the 2024 refit.

1.2.5 Model Dataset

The latest refit used graft outcomes from 50â€¯769 adult, firstâ€‘time, deceasedâ€‘donor kidneyâ€‘alone transplants performed in the United States between 2018Â andÂ 2021 (followâ€‘up through JuneÂ 2024).

1.2.6 Reference Donor Definition

The reference donor (KDRIÂ =Â 1.0) has:

  • AgeÂ 40Â yr
  • HeightÂ 170Â cm
  • WeightÂ \(\ge\)Â 80Â kg
  • No diabetes
  • No hypertension
  • Cause of death other than cerebrovascular accident
  • Terminal creatinineÂ =Â 1.0Â mg/dL
  • Brainâ€‘death donor (notÂ donation after cardiac death)

All other donors are compared against this reference profile.

1.2.10 Applicability

KDRI applies only to deceased donors. Livingâ€‘donor analogues such as the Living Kidney Donor Profile Index (LKDPI)\(^{5}\) are not used for allocation.

1.3 The Kidney Donor Profile Index (KDPI)

1.3.1 Definition

KDPI is defined as the percentile rank (0â€“100%) of a donor kidneyâ€™s Scaled KDRI against the U.S. donor pool from the previous calendar year.

1.3.2 Calculation

First calaulate the Scaled KDRI using the following formular.

\[ \mathrm{KDRI}_{\text{SCALED}} = \frac{\mathrm{KDRI}_{\text{RAO}}}{\text{scaling factor}} \]

The â€œscaling factorâ€ is the median \(\mathrm{KDRI}_{\text{RAO}}\) value among all kidney donors recovered during the previous calendar year (e.g.Â scaling factor = 1.404 in 2024).

Let \(F_{\text{year}}\) be the empirical cumulative distribution function (CDF) of Scaled KDRI values for deceased donors in a given reference year. Then

\(\text{KDPI} = 100\% \times F_{\text{year}}(\mathrm{KDRI}_{\text{SCALED}}).\)

1.3.3 Annual Reference Distribution

  • The 2024 OPTN guide illustrates KDPI using 2022 donor data\(^{2}\).
  • The most recent public mapping file is based on 2023 donors\(^{3}\).

Hence KDPI reflects yearâ€‘toâ€‘year changes in donor risk.

1.3.4 Worked Example

A donor with KDRIÂ =Â 1.51 lies at the 90th percentile of the 2023 donor distribution : KDPIÂ =Â 90%.

1.3.5 Evaluation of KDPI (C-Index)

The predictive power of the KDPI is moderate of C-Index = 0.6.

2. EPTS: Estimated Postâ€‘Transplant Survival Score

2.1 Definition and Purpose

The Estimated Postâ€‘Transplant Survival (EPTS) score (0â€“100%) estimates how long a candidate is expected to live after transplantation. Lower scores imply longer expected survival. Kidneys with KDPIÂ \(\le\)Â 20% are offered first to candidates with EPTSÂ \(\le\)Â 20%.

2.2 Origin

Developed by the Scientific Registry of Transplant Recipients (SRTR) for the OPTN Kidney Committee\(^{4}\).

2.3 Usage Conditions

  • Applies only to adult candidates (\(\ge\)â€¯18â€¯yr).
  • Priority rule: KDPIÂ \(\le\)â€¯20% kidneys â†’ candidates with EPTSÂ \(\le\)â€¯20%.

2.4 Raw EPTS Formula

\[ \begin{aligned} \text{Raw EPTS} =\ & 0.047 \times \max(\text{Age} - 25,\ 0) - 0.015 \times \text{Diabetes} \times \max(\text{Age} - 25,\ 0) \\ & + 0.398 \times \text{Prior Solid Organ Transplant} - 0.237 \times \text{Diabetes} \times \text{Prior Organ Transplant} \\ & + 0.315 \times \log(\text{Years on Dialysis} + 1) - 0.099 \times \text{Diabetes} \times \log(\text{Years on Dialysis} + 1) \\ & + 0.130 \times I(\text{Years on Dialysis} = 0) - 0.348 \times \text{Diabetes} \times I(\text{Years on Dialysis} = 0) + 1.262 \times \text{Diabetes} \end{aligned} \]

  • log() denotes the natural logarithm.

  • IndicatorÂ \(I(\cdot)\) equalsÂ 1 if the condition is true, otherwiseÂ 0.

  • Binary covariates Diabetes and PriorÂ Tx take valueÂ 1 when present andÂ 0 otherwise.

The final EPTS score is the percentile of the raw score within the national adult waitâ€‘list on 31â€¯DecÂ 2023 (updated annually).

2.5 Model Variables

The four predictors in the original Cox model were: age, diabetes, prior transplant history, and dialysis duration.

2.6 Model History

OPTN is exploring a Composite Allocation Score (CAS) that aggregates ten attributesâ€”KDPI/EPTS matching, waiting time, geography, HLA, etc.â€”into a single 0â€“100 scale.

2.7 Interpretation

  • EPTSÂ =Â 0%Â : longest expected survival
  • EPTSÂ =Â 100%Â : shortest expected survival
  • EPTSÂ \(\le\)â€¯20% triggers priority for KDPIÂ \(\le\)â€¯20% kidneys.
